Joystick Controlled DC Motor with Speed Indicator LEDs

This project uses a joystick to control a DC motor and three LEDs as a speed indicator.  
The motor speed is mapped from the joystick X-axis, while the LEDs show low, medium, or high speed.

This project helps beginners learn:
- Reading analog joystick input  
- Controlling DC motor direction and speed with PWM  
- Using LEDs as indicators for speed levels  
- Using `Serial.print()` for debugging  

---

Arduino Code

```cpp
// JOYSTICK
int xPin = A0;
int yPin = A1;
int sPin = 2;
int xVal;
int yVal;
int sVal;

// DC MOTOR
int speedPin = 5;
int dir1 = 4;
int dir2 = 3;
int speed;

// LED
int redLed = 11;
int yellowLed = 9;
int greenLed = 6;
int bright = 200;
int dt = 200;

void setup() {
  // JOYSTICK
  pinMode(xPin, INPUT);
  pinMode(yPin, INPUT);
  pinMode(sPin, INPUT);
  digitalWrite(sPin, HIGH); // Enable internal pull-up
  Serial.begin(9600);

  // DC MOTOR
  pinMode(dir1, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(dir2, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(speedPin, OUTPUT);

  // LED
  pinMode(redLed, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(yellowLed, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(greenLed, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  // Set motor direction
  digitalWrite(dir1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(dir2, LOW);

  // Read joystick X-axis
  xVal = analogRead(xPin);
  speed = (255.0 / 1023.0) * xVal;
  Serial.println(speed);
  delay(dt);

  // Control motor speed
  analogWrite(speedPin, speed);

  // LED indicators
  if (speed < 100) {
    analogWrite(redLed, bright);
    digitalWrite(greenLed, LOW);
    digitalWrite(yellowLed, LOW);
  } else if (speed >= 100 && speed < 180) {
    digitalWrite(redLed, LOW);
    digitalWrite(greenLed, LOW);
    analogWrite(yellowLed, bright);
  } else if (speed >= 180) {
    digitalWrite(redLed, LOW);
    analogWrite(greenLed, bright);
    digitalWrite(yellowLed, LOW);
  }
}
```

---

Circuit Setup

**Components needed:**
- Arduino Uno (or compatible board)  
- 1 × Joystick module  
- 1 × DC motor with motor driver (L298N, L293D, or similar)  
- 3 × LEDs (red, yellow, green)  
- 3 × 220Ω resistors  
- Breadboard  
- Jumper wires  

Wiring Instructions:
1. **Joystick**  
   - X-axis → A0  
   - Y-axis → A1  
   - Switch → pin 2  
   - VCC → 5V, GND → GND  

2. DC Motor  
   - Connect motor driver inputs to pins 3, 4 (dir1, dir2)  
   - PWM speed → pin 5  
   - Motor power → driver 5V or external supply  
   - Motor outputs → DC motor  

3. LEDs 
   - Red LED anode → pin 11 through 220Ω resistor, cathode → GND  
   - Yellow LED anode → pin 9 through 220Ω resistor, cathode → GND  
   - Green LED anode → pin 6 through 220Ω resistor, cathode → GND  

How it works:
- Joystick X-axis controls motor speed (0–255 PWM).  
- Motor always rotates in one direction (dir1 HIGH, dir2 LOW).  
- Red LED = low speed, Yellow LED = medium speed, Green LED = high speed.  
- Serial Monitor prints the motor speed every 200ms.  

I had a lot of fun with this easy project so enjoy it :)

